node.text: This month I’ve chosen to share the three books that I will NEVER give away. Usually, I chew through books, give them to a friend, or exchange them with my mom, but these three are part of my permanent library: “A Million Little Pieces” by @jamesfrey_, “After Visiting Friends” by @Michael_Hainey, and “A Little Life” by @hanyayanagihara. If you haven’t read them, it’s time. Head to the link in my bio or my story to shop them now. PS Please let me know if these books resonate as much with you as they do with me – and why!

node.text: When it comes to comfortable furniture, our Soriana sofa checks all the boxes. First designed in Italy by Tobia Scarpa in 1969, the Soriana sofa is renowned as one of the best designs from the 1970s. @jeremiahbrent and I bought this sofa together when we first moved to LA and have since recovered it many, many times. Head to @1stdibs to look for classic pieces like this or to track down something similar (and squishy)!

node.text: When I look back on my 25-year career in design, I think my top inspiration for so many of the decisions that I make in design -whether it’s redecorating a room, or designing pieces for @livingspaces - has to be the French 1950s. What was going on at the time? Well for one, most of the furniture from that period from French designers, like Jean-Michel Frank, was actually being manufactured in Beirut, Lebanon. The materials of this era were parchment and bronze and thick linen over simple and chic upholstered shapes. The design wasn’t fussy, it was super clean and when I think of mid-century, I automatically look to French design to define the era.

node.text: We decorated this model residence at the Marlow.  A  newly renovated prewar building on Manhattan’s Upper West Side. We kept the color palette muted and selected a beautiful mix of furnishings, textiles, and textures that bring the space to life. We sourced abstract art from Axel Abbott, @AlexSofferArt, and @NancySmithFineArt along with vintage furnishings (obviously). Like a 1950s sheepskin wingback chair from Fritz Hansen and an adjustable Lundia chair from Dutch designer Gijs Boelaars. @jeremiahbrent

node.text: The Viennese Secessionist Movement and the Wiener Werkstätte were two movements in Vienna around the turn of the century best represented by the famous painting by Gustav Klimt, “The Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer”. The palette, colors, and free use of gold leaf in this painting can be seen in #architecture and #design from this era — The Church of St. Leopold designed by Otto Wagner and Hotel Paul Mezzara by architect Hector Guimard are just two examples of how this painting was a constant source of inspiration for the period. Designer and Architect Josef Hoffmann is another amazing example from this era, and you can still find his pieces, either vintage or made as reproductions, today. His work is amongst the most simple, refined, and elegant designs that I absolutely love.

node.text: No matter what we do for a living, all of us have had these moments when something feels so disappointing but in hindsight, you realize that it was all meant to be. 30 years ago I had a soul-crushing “no” and it ended up being the best thing that ever happened to me. I’m sharing this story to encourage anyone who might be feeling dejected or disappointed to KEEP. GOING. Because you never know how powerful these moments of redirection can really be.

node.text: OK, so this is something really different: I sat down with the @MeditativeStory team who asked me to share a truly transformative moment in my life. Not necessarily something huge and dramatic, but a small moment that became a defining one. Think about that for a moment...Also, the idea of what #meditation is. It isn’t just getting quiet in nature — It can also be these deeply personal moments we go through in our lives that become the basis for incredible self-discovery. The #podcast is out today so take a listen and let me know what you think 🎧. Link in my bio or visit listen.meditativestory.com/nateberkus #MeditativeStory @rohantakesphotos
